1
00:00:09,240 --> 00:00:11,600
Hare Krishna. Yes, Prabhu. Some questions?

2
00:00:11,720 --> 00:00:17,640
Dandavat, Mahārāja! We have a question from Krishnapada Prabhu, Salt Lake City.

3
00:00:17,640 --> 00:00:22,240
We hear Śrīla Guru Mahārāj
saying that the environment is not the problem,

4
00:00:22,240 --> 00:00:28,240
that we ourselves are the problem and not
to quarrel with the environment. But say,

5
00:00:28,250 --> 00:00:34,820
when you are in a hot atmosphere and you are
wearing too many layers, do you not take off

6
00:00:34,820 --> 00:00:41,090
some layers, move to a cooler spot or make
an adjustment to that environment?

7
00:00:41,090 --> 00:00:45,950
Could you speak about this according to the perspective of our spiritual life?

8
00:00:49,440 --> 00:00:57,200
In the Bhagavad-gītā
Krishna tells Arjuna:

9
00:00:57,200 --> 00:01:04,120
mātrā-sparśās tu kaunteya śītoṣṇa-sukha-duḥkha-dāḥ

10
00:01:04,120 --> 00:01:10,760
āgamāpāyino ’nityās tāṁs titikṣasva bhārata
[Bhagavad-gītā 2.14]

11
00:01:10,760 --> 00:01:21,000
He says that the environment, karmic circumstances
we are surrounded by, and literally, the world

12
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:31,480
we find ourselves in, He compares to seasonal changes.

13
00:01:31,480 --> 00:01:40,920
And His advice is tolerance, tāṁs titikṣasva

14
00:01:40,920 --> 00:01:50,159
to tolerate it. And as He says,
Krishnapada in the question. So,

15
00:01:50,159 --> 00:01:56,439
if necessary you remove some layers, or open
an umbrella, or put on more, according to

16
00:01:56,439 --> 00:02:15,030
the circumstance. But that is not to blame
the environment or the circumstances as the

17
00:02:15,030 --> 00:02:23,240
sole cause of your suffering. It’s a superficial
cause of suffering. But what is at the heart

18
00:02:23,240 --> 00:02:38,610
of the matter, the root of the matter is something
else, that has placed us in this circumstance.

19
00:02:38,610 --> 00:02:48,870
Ichchhā-dveṣa-samutthena dvandva-mohena
bhārata [Bhagavad-gītā 7.27]. Again in

20
00:02:48,870 --> 00:02:58,290
the Gītā. And in Manu Saṁhitā: tamasā
bahu rūpeṇa veśṭitāḥ karmahetunā.

21
00:02:58,290 --> 00:03:10,260
Manu says, “All these different life forms
you see…” And as I’ve told, the body

22
00:03:10,260 --> 00:03:17,000
is the biological expression of the soul’s
delusion. And what is it based on?

23
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:33,240
Veśṭitāḥ karmahetunā, we’re all dressed in our karma—which is more to the point.

24
00:03:33,260 --> 00:03:42,319
We have generated the circumstances that we
find ourselves in. Even from a scientific

25
00:03:42,319 --> 00:03:48,930
point of view, for every action there’s
an equal and opposite reaction. And when the

26
00:03:48,930 --> 00:03:57,620
subject of karma comes up in the Gītā, Krishna
to Arjuna, it’s interesting to note that

27
00:03:57,620 --> 00:04:10,960
the first thing Krishna says to Arjuna—and
I’m paraphrasing—is, “It’s complicated.”

28
00:04:10,960 --> 00:04:16,720
All right, or as Prabhupād said, “The intricacies of karma are difficult to know.” It’s complicated.

29
00:04:17,880 --> 00:04:29,060
What does it say? “Even the experts are
bewildered,” I forget the verse, but it’s

30
00:04:29,060 --> 00:04:34,349
saying, “in trying to understand the intricacies
of karma. It’s very complicated.” Because

31
00:04:34,349 --> 00:04:40,139
you’re in a situation as a human being,
where you’re making real-time choices, and

32
00:04:40,139 --> 00:04:50,780
that will have a future outcome. But you also
have the results, the reactions of former

33
00:04:50,780 --> 00:04:55,760
actions, in different stages of development
and expression.

34
00:04:55,760 --> 00:05:01,830
Rūpa Goswāmī discusses this quoting the Padma-purāṇa in the Bhakti-rasāmṛta-sindhu,

35
00:05:01,830 --> 00:05:10,180
and he said, “Some karmic reactions are
in seed form, some of them have sprouted,

36
00:05:10,180 --> 00:05:18,789
some have flowered, and some are bearing fruit.”
So they’re in all different stages of expression

37
00:05:18,800 --> 00:05:28,400
and in the midst of that you’re making real-time
choices. So, Krishna tells Arjuna, “It’s complicated,”

38
00:05:28,400 --> 00:05:33,640
but nonetheless, it is…
If for every action there’s an equal and

39
00:05:33,669 --> 00:05:42,249
opposite reaction, in that sense, it’s warranted.
We are responsible for the karmic circumstances

40
00:05:42,249 --> 00:05:52,500
that we find ourselves in. So, the message
of the Gītā, as He alludes here, Śrīla

41
00:05:52,500 --> 00:05:58,849
Guru Mahārāja is saying, “Not to quarrel
with the environment,” but, as the aphorism

42
00:05:58,849 --> 00:06:10,870
is there, or the cliché: “Healer heal thyself.”
Make an inner adjustment.

43
00:06:10,880 --> 00:06:21,840
But if we want to pursue this line of thought
deeper, then—the pages o f the Bhāgavatam,

44
00:06:21,840 --> 00:06:25,559
there’re the Brahmā-stuti, the prayers
of Brahmā:

45
00:06:25,560 --> 00:06:32,880
tat te ’nukampāṁ su-samīkṣamāṇo
bhuñjāna evātma-kṛtaṁ vipākam

46
00:06:32,880 --> 00:06:39,590
[Śrīmad Bhāgavatam 10.14.8]

47
00:06:39,590 --> 00:06:50,449
Su-samīkṣa is the word that he [Lord Brahmā]
used. Samīkṣa means ‘to analyze.’ But

48
00:06:50,449 --> 00:07:05,000
su-samīkṣa means ‘to scrutinize’—to
analyze very acutely, to take it to another level.

49
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:10,960
Tat te ’nukampāṁ su-samīkṣamāṇo.
So, in Guru Mahārāja’s words, “These

50
00:07:10,979 --> 00:07:18,059
karmic circumstances that you find yourself
in, (that, footnote, we’ve generated), they’re

51
00:07:18,059 --> 00:07:32,869
not to your liking or we're suffering .”Is it
meant to take you down, to undo you? Or is

52
00:07:32,880 --> 00:07:41,360
there some way to interpret this in a positive light?”

53
00:07:41,360 --> 00:07:47,879
“Here,” Guru Mahārāja says, “the devotee,
one with more advanced spiritual vision, with

54
00:07:47,880 --> 00:07:54,600
greater depth, seeing beyond the superficial
aspect of any circumstance or situation, able

55
00:07:54,600 --> 00:08:04,590
will be able to see deeper, will see the friendly hand
of Krishna in the background.”

56
00:08:04,590 --> 00:08:18,349
Like the test. We know teachers do a flash-quiz,
a pop-quiz—it goes by various names. Unannounced

57
00:08:18,349 --> 00:08:25,710
they decide to test the students. Why? Because
the teacher may have the impression that they’re

58
00:08:25,710 --> 00:08:38,310
only feigning comprehension. So to see where
they’re at, as a whole, in terms of imbibing

59
00:08:38,310 --> 00:08:50,110
the teachings. An unannounced pop-quiz is
given. Let’s say, “Now close the books,”

60
00:08:50,110 --> 00:09:08,650
and here comes this test. And it’s usually
met with groans, or some irritation, or annoyance.

61
00:09:08,650 --> 00:09:19,400
But why is the teacher doing this? Someone
might think like, “Our teacher is very mean.

62
00:09:19,400 --> 00:09:30,560
It’s not a nice teacher, not a good teacher.”
But really, is that the case, or is it that

63
00:09:30,580 --> 00:09:41,390
the teacher is really doing a service to the
students by this test coming, being given,

64
00:09:41,390 --> 00:09:55,050
will allow them to identify upon the things
that they do not comprehend properly? To give

65
00:09:55,050 --> 00:10:03,080
that their focus, their attention. It’ll
be revealed through testing

66
00:10:03,080 --> 00:10:13,440
where the flaws are, where one needs to develop.

67
00:10:13,440 --> 00:10:25,160
So, the greater the depths of devotional vision, the more favourable the interpretation of the circumstances.

68
00:10:25,160 --> 00:10:31,920
We hear of Queen Kunti:

69
00:10:31,920 --> 00:10:39,440
vipadaḥ santu tāḥ śaśvat
tatra tatra jagad-guro

70
00:10:39,440 --> 00:10:42,960
bhavato darśanaṁ yat syād
apunar bhava-darśanam

71
00:10:42,960 --> 00:10:44,400
[Śrīmad Bhāgavatam 1.8.25]

72
00:10:44,400 --> 00:10:53,720
She’s reflecting upon her pastimes with
Krishna and the Pāṇḍavas. And we know,

73
00:10:53,720 --> 00:10:58,400
the Pāṇḍavas repeatedly were put into
very dangerous situations, life-threatening

74
00:10:58,400 --> 00:11:09,620
situations. And the point of emphasis from
her is that upon reflection she realizes:

75
00:11:09,620 --> 00:11:22,640
those were the times of the greatest intensity of her focus, remembrance, dependence, taking

76
00:11:22,640 --> 00:11:34,570
shelter. And that other times, when things
were seemingly fine and going on normally,

77
00:11:34,570 --> 00:11:42,360
that there was a tendency to be distracted
from that which is substantial. To become

78
00:11:42,360 --> 00:11:53,320
forgetful or complacent. So, she’s so advanced that she comes to the conclusion, saying:

79
00:11:53,320 --> 00:11:56,640
vipadaḥ santu tāḥ śaśvat
tatra tatra jagad-guro

80
00:11:56,640 --> 00:12:00,240
bhavato darśanaṁ yat syād
apunar bhava-darśanam

81
00:12:00,240 --> 00:12:02,080
[Śrīmad Bhāgavatam 1.8.25]

82
00:12:02,080 --> 00:12:06,920
“By having darśana of You, through remembrance
of You…” Then—bhava-darśanam,

83
00:12:06,940 --> 00:12:13,860
“you don’t have to see, experience this world
of suffering any more.” So, it would be

84
00:12:13,860 --> 00:12:25,520
then, “If adverse circumstances compel me
to enter that level, that depth of focus,

85
00:12:25,520 --> 00:12:33,040
concentration, remembrance, then adversity
would be good for me.” Now we know, no one

86
00:12:33,040 --> 00:12:39,400
is inviting adversity other than Queen Kunti.
But she has achieved that level.

87
00:12:39,400 --> 00:12:45,600
That’s her level of interpretation.

88
00:12:45,600 --> 00:12:49,000
So, again in the Gītā:

89
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:53,000
bhoktāraṁ yajña-tapasāṁ
sarva-loka-maheśvaram

90
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:54,160
[Bhagavad-gītā 5.29]

91
00:12:54,160 --> 00:13:00,280
[Krishna is saying,] bhoktāraṁ—everything
is meant for his enjoyment. Yajña-tapasāṁ,

92
00:13:00,300 --> 00:13:10,490
all yajñas, tapasya. He is what? It’s said,
yajño vai viṣṇuḥ from the Vedas, and

93
00:13:10,490 --> 00:13:26,210
Yajñeśvar. That’s why Brahmā was vimohan,
bewildered to see… He’s thinking, “Normally

94
00:13:26,210 --> 00:13:33,630
the Lord is worshipped with yajña. There’s
a big sacrifice and then there’s the offering.

95
00:13:33,630 --> 00:13:42,190
He eats only what is offered through yajña.
And here I am to believe that this five-year-old

96
00:13:42,190 --> 00:13:49,850
boy sitting on the banks of the Yamunā with
His cowherd boyfriends and His calves, and

97
00:13:49,850 --> 00:13:57,070
they’re frolicking about, and they’re
having a picnic—He can do that too? The One,

98
00:13:57,070 --> 00:14:05,630
who, we’re told, only eats through yajña?”
And he learned about the aprākṛta-līlā

99
00:14:05,640 --> 00:14:13,280
of Krishna, the human-like pastimes of the
central conception of the Infinite.

100
00:14:13,280 --> 00:14:18,080
But: bhoktāraṁ yajña-tapasāṁ
sarva-loka-maheśvaram

101
00:14:18,080 --> 00:14:19,480
[Bhagavad-gītā 5.29]

102
00:14:19,480 --> 00:14:26,910
“He’s controlling everything.”
There’s that saying, “Not a blade of grass

103
00:14:26,910 --> 00:14:36,270
moves without the will of God.” Guru Mahārāja
would extend it to dust. So, whatever you

104
00:14:36,270 --> 00:14:41,450
conceive of the finest thing, not moving without
a will of God—the electron, the neutron,

105
00:14:41,450 --> 00:14:59,360
the proton, the quark. Then one would have
to question, “If on that level the movement

106
00:14:59,360 --> 00:15:08,880
is attributed to divinity, then what to speak
of things that are seemingly more significant

107
00:15:08,880 --> 00:15:17,830
then that?— In the background: the divine, divinity”.
So, then we’ll have to think,

108
00:15:17,830 --> 00:15:30,040
“Is this meant to take me down? It’s meant
to make me fail or pass to the next level?

109
00:15:30,050 --> 00:15:40,940
Is He inimical to me or friendly to me? Who’s
controlling all circumstances is my enemy

110
00:15:40,940 --> 00:15:47,870
or my friend?” [Who] has my self-interest
at heart, and not only myself—the whole

111
00:15:47,870 --> 00:15:57,050
animation, in the words of Guru Mahārāja.
And throw in the inanimate as well.

112
00:15:57,050 --> 00:15:59,510
Next line:
bhoktāraṁ yajña-tapasāṁ

113
00:15:59,510 --> 00:16:03,780
sarva-loka-maheśvaram
suhṛdaṁ sarva-bhūtānāṁ

114
00:16:03,780 --> 00:16:05,120
[Bhagavad-gītā 5.29]

115
00:16:05,120 --> 00:16:17,300
Because what was said in the first two lines
might give one pause. “Supreme enjoyer controlling

116
00:16:17,300 --> 00:16:25,040
everything.”—What about us? What about you—suhṛdaṁ
sarva-bhūtānāṁ, “and He’s the dearmost

117
00:16:25,040 --> 00:16:29,980
friend of every living being.” So, like
in this world,

118
00:16:29,980 --> 00:16:32,760
it’s not what you know, but who you know.

119
00:16:32,760 --> 00:16:39,100
If the person you know—and
not just know, but is your dearmost friend—

120
00:16:39,100 --> 00:16:47,980
is controlling everything, then it cannot be
against your self-interest. And this point,

121
00:16:47,980 --> 00:16:55,380
to embrace this, to understand this, to have
faith and the truth of this…

122
00:16:55,380 --> 00:17:04,080
Suhṛdaṁ sarva-bhūtānāṁ—what does Krishna say—jñātvā māṁ śāntim ṛchchhati, “knowing this

123
00:17:04,080 --> 00:17:09,620
if you can know this, and believe this, [and]
embrace this understanding, then

124
00:17:09,630 --> 00:17:16,660
"jñātvāmāṁ śāntim ṛchchhati, “then you’ll
be free from anxiety and peaceful,

125
00:17:16,660 --> 00:17:23,240
knowing that Krishna’s friendly hand is in the background of all events.”

126
00:17:30,780 --> 00:17:43,760
We’re living in a world of mortality. When
events transpire in such a way is to make

127
00:17:43,760 --> 00:17:57,320
that inescapably obvious, we’re upset. Because
we prefer to—what’s the word, when you’re…

128
00:17:57,320 --> 00:18:06,240
I guess ‘oblivious’ is one word—to be
oblivious to our mailing address, which is

129
00:18:06,240 --> 00:18:17,600
the world of mortality. So we want it to be
kept as far away as possible, not to rain

130
00:18:17,600 --> 00:18:24,680
on our little parade of exploitation.

131
00:18:24,680 --> 00:18:30,040
And then the Latin phrase
memento mori—death reminders

132
00:18:30,040 --> 00:18:36,580
which is supposed to be one of
the themes of art.

133
00:18:36,580 --> 00:18:43,720
And by that, we don’t just mean paintings, but may mean literature. When, if it’s to be taken seriously, it

134
00:18:43,720 --> 00:18:53,400
must deal with one of these subjects. Memento mori, death reminders.

135
00:18:57,180 --> 00:19:06,480
We hear that Chekhov is arguably the greatest short-story writer of all time.

136
00:19:06,480 --> 00:19:12,080
And so everyone should read a little Chekhov. [LAUGHING]

137
00:19:12,080 --> 00:19:19,060
What’s the name? It’s called “Ionych” [aɪ’ənɪʧ]?

138
00:19:19,060 --> 00:19:26,700
Okay, “Ionych” [iː’ɔənɪʧ], not
‘ion’ [‘aɪən]. “Ionych” [iː’ɔənɪʧ].

139
00:19:26,700 --> 00:19:33,180
[LAUGHING] I still think he could have chosen
a better title for it, but I’m not Chekhov.

140
00:19:33,180 --> 00:19:38,050
[LAUGHING] But in this story, just to give
an example, I thought, well, if he’s supposed

141
00:19:38,050 --> 00:19:42,620
to be this great writer, and a short story
is supposed to be the hardest kind of story

142
00:19:42,620 --> 00:19:48,390
to write, because they can have no…, nothing
unnecessary can be introduced there. Some,

143
00:19:48,390 --> 00:19:56,010
So, “What is this story about?” And, if it’s
consistent with the themes of great literature,

144
00:19:56,010 --> 00:20:04,640
then memento mori could definitely be one
of the themes. And in a nutshell, a man at

145
00:20:04,640 --> 00:20:14,980
a party in Petersburg is obsessed with a girl
who’s like a musician, dancer, singer that type

146
00:20:14,980 --> 00:20:25,420
She is much younger than [him],
he is enamoured. And she’s not unaware of that

147
00:20:25,420 --> 00:20:32,840
So, before the party ends, she passes
a note to him saying, ‘Meet me in the cemetery

148
00:20:32,850 --> 00:20:42,390
at midnight.’ So, when he goes home he still
has…, his intelligence is still operating

149
00:20:42,390 --> 00:20:51,920
at this point, and he’s thinking, “I’m
not such a fool! This girl is just toying

150
00:20:51,920 --> 00:20:58,290
with me. ‘Meet me in the graveyard, the
cemetery, at midnight.’ I’m not that kind

151
00:20:58,290 --> 00:21:06,520
of foolish man.” But that’s how he was
thinking around 10:30. As the clock started

152
00:21:06,520 --> 00:21:12,370
going more towards midnight, and he started
to think, “What if she actually goes and

153
00:21:12,370 --> 00:21:22,820
I’m not there.” [LAUGHING] Like the praying
mantis she was eating his brain.

154
00:21:22,820 --> 00:21:29,040
We saw a praying mantis today—if someone wonders where that came from. Anyway. So, he’s thinking

155
00:21:29,050 --> 00:21:39,340
if I’m... on the odd chance that she’s serious,
I should go there. And he gets his driver

156
00:21:39,340 --> 00:21:49,710
takes him to the cemetery. And midnight hour,
the bewitching hour comes. But no bewitcher,

157
00:21:49,710 --> 00:21:59,460
she does not show. He is there alone, and
he decides to walk through the cemetery.

158
00:21:59,460 --> 00:22:10,640
And as he’s walking through the cemetery he’s observing the names and dates, birth dates

159
00:22:10,640 --> 00:22:20,450
and death dates, on the gravestones. And it
occurs to him that they were young men, women

160
00:22:20,450 --> 00:22:28,980
like he and that girl. They also had hopes,
aspirations, loves, plans.

161
00:22:28,980 --> 00:22:35,600
As John Lennon said in his song, “Life is
what happens to you while you’re busy making

162
00:22:35,600 --> 00:22:47,500
other plans.” Three months ago people were
busy making other plans, then all their plans

163
00:22:47,500 --> 00:22:56,240
came to an end. Just like everyone, who had
survived, they’re full of plans, hopes,

164
00:22:56,240 --> 00:23:08,309
conventional aspirations. Not unlike anyone
else, not a particular class of people, not

165
00:23:08,309 --> 00:23:19,480
unlike anyone else. And then all of those
plans finished because this is the world of mortality.

166
00:23:19,480 --> 00:23:24,890
And I thought when… about Chekhov. So, he’s arguably the greatest story writer,

167
00:23:24,890 --> 00:23:32,840
and I thought, this underscores how excellent
he is at storytelling. He’s telling you

168
00:23:32,840 --> 00:23:41,820
a story, in essence, setting up something
that doesn’t happen. A lesser writer would

169
00:23:41,820 --> 00:23:51,700
think about what happens. He’s so masterful.
He’s telling you something… What you anticipate

170
00:23:51,700 --> 00:23:59,040
will happen, does not happen. The girl doesn’t
come. You think, “So what kind of a story is that?”

171
00:23:59,040 --> 00:24:10,120
It’s a better story because
of her not showing. That leads him on this

172
00:24:10,120 --> 00:24:20,060
tour of the cemetery, of the graveyard, and
he realizes… As the verse Guru Mahārāja

173
00:24:20,060 --> 00:24:24,340
liked to quote from Gray’s Elegy (Gurudev
liked it so much as well):

174
00:24:24,340 --> 00:24:31,600
The boast of heraldry, the pomp of pow'r,
And all that beauty, all that wealth e'er gave,

175
00:24:31,600 --> 00:24:34,380
Awaits alike th' inevitable hour.

176
00:24:34,380 --> 00:24:39,610
The paths of glory lead but to the grave.
[Thomas Gray, Elegy Written in a Country Churchyard]

177
00:24:39,610 --> 00:24:45,740
So he dealt with that issue, that’s why
it’s considered to be art.

178
00:24:45,740 --> 00:24:52,920
It’s not something we should run away from,
but we should confront.

179
00:24:52,920 --> 00:25:03,280
Shakespeare, “Out, out, brief candle!”
