preaching in his village, and the lead preacher

361
00:47:10,270 --> 00:47:21,010
told them, ‘Your father will die, your mother
will die, this whole world will vanish. Then

362
00:47:21,010 --> 00:47:25,580
what will you do? Your father is nothing,
your mother is nothing, this world is nothing—it

363
00:47:25,580 --> 00:47:33,160
will all vanish. Then what?’” And Gurudev
introduced it by saying, “He came talking

364
00:47:33,160 --> 00:47:38,770
this nonsense—mother is nothing, father
is nothing, world there’s nothing, it will

365
00:47:38,770 --> 00:47:52,200
all vanish. But it struck a sympathetic chord
in my heart and I could not deny its truth,

366
00:47:52,200 --> 00:47:53,440
the validity.”

367
00:48:07,200 --> 00:48:17,940
Still, the one other thing I wanted to say
was, when we were told that during this period

368
00:48:17,940 --> 00:48:27,160
the safest thing to do is self-isolation,
to go into isolation.

369
00:48:32,600 --> 00:48:40,780
And for some, that’s very difficult to do, for some less, but it’s the advice

370
00:48:40,780 --> 00:48:43,620
‘to stop all the social interaction.’

371
00:48:45,280 --> 00:48:53,760
And as a side point, it’s interesting to
note that, due to the temporary suspension

372
00:48:53,760 --> 00:49:00,970
of economic development and everything that
goes with it, blue skies have returned, clear

373
00:49:00,970 --> 00:49:15,910
water in Venice due to no tourists or no manufacturing.
And before we go back to business as usual,

374
00:49:15,910 --> 00:49:21,100
maybe some adjustments should be made. Look
at that blue sky and think about it if there’s

375
00:49:21,100 --> 00:49:26,180
some adjustment you can make. Look at that
clear water. That’s a side point, but dealing

376
00:49:26,180 --> 00:49:30,840
with the principle of isolation.

377
00:49:34,690 --> 00:49:43,040
I was telling Krishna Kanta DD and Munindra
that one time when I was living in Europe,

378
00:49:43,040 --> 00:49:49,410
there was some discrepancy with my international
driver’s licence, and I was going from Austria

379
00:49:49,410 --> 00:50:04,900
to Germany, and—you know that German precision
[and] proficiency—they noted that. And somehow—I’m

380
00:50:04,900 --> 00:50:13,660
giving the condensed version—I was incarcerated,
which for those who don’t know what’s

381
00:50:13,660 --> 00:50:22,450
‘incarcerate,’ I was thrown in jail in
solitary confinement immediately. And I was

382
00:50:22,450 --> 00:50:28,099
presented to a judge, and through a German
interpreter, the lady told me with a smile

383
00:50:28,100 --> 00:50:40,320
on her face, “This matter should be resolved
in three weeks. Entschuldigen Sie bitte.”

384
00:50:45,530 --> 00:50:53,440
I went to my cell wearing these woolen pants
and the woolen coat. I asked if I could have

385
00:50:53,450 --> 00:51:00,710
two things—my japa-mālā and a volume [of]
Śrī Chaitanya-charitāmṛta, and they consented

386
00:51:00,710 --> 00:51:15,210
to that. So, I was in the cell chanting and
thinking, “I need to keep my composure.”

387
00:51:15,210 --> 00:51:24,340
If I allow this confinement to… If I lose
my composure in confinement, I’m going to

388
00:51:24,340 --> 00:51:38,720
lose my mind, and be tormented mentally, psychically.
So I started having a dialogue with myself.

389
00:51:38,720 --> 00:51:46,880
And it ran something like this—I was saying,
“Your whole life you spend in a room this

390
00:51:46,880 --> 00:51:57,200
size, so now you’re in a room this size,
you’re always in a room this size, so don’t

391
00:51:57,200 --> 00:52:02,130
be disturbed by that, it’s just a different
location, but you spend your whole life in

392
00:52:02,130 --> 00:52:08,730
a room this size.” But then the other part
of the dialogue said, “But there’s a difference.”

393
00:52:08,730 --> 00:52:14,050
At that time I was living in Vienna [and]
it’s true, this room and the room in Vienna

394
00:52:14,050 --> 00:52:23,680
are a similar size. “The difference is,
you decide to be in that room in Vienna and

395
00:52:23,680 --> 00:52:28,770
you did not make the choice to be in this
room.” So the difference between these two

396
00:52:28,770 --> 00:52:39,170
rooms is freedom. It’s not the room that’s
the difficulty. Your freedom has been taken

397
00:52:39,170 --> 00:52:46,450
from you. You don’t have a choice. The room
in Vienna—you can decide not to be in there,

398
00:52:46,450 --> 00:52:54,440
to go for a walk, or do whatever is necessary.
In this room, you cannot decide not to be here.

399
00:52:54,440 --> 00:53:05,270
You can only be here. And then I thought,
“This is a problem.” I thought, “Yeah,

400
00:53:05,270 --> 00:53:11,420
that’s my freedom.” It’s the freedom.
It’s not the size of the room, it’s that

401
00:53:11,420 --> 00:53:17,140
I’ve lost my freedom, my choice.

402
00:53:17,140 --> 00:53:24,390
We’re told, it’s so innate to the existence
of the jīva, you cannot remove the free will.

403
00:53:24,390 --> 00:53:29,060
Because in Jaiva-dharma at one point it’s
brought up that, “Well, if it’s by misuse

404
00:53:29,060 --> 00:53:36,040
of the free will of the jīva that brings
them into the suffering condition—

405
00:53:36,040 --> 00:53:44,340
take away the free will, make it so that they can only
be happy-happy-happy all the time…time…time…”

406
00:53:45,960 --> 00:53:50,540
And Bhakti Vinod’s answered, he said, “No,
understand, it’s so innate; if you remove

407
00:53:50,540 --> 00:53:56,880
free will from the jīva, jīva doesn’t
exist anymore.”

408
00:53:56,880 --> 00:54:06,400
And somehow I see a connection between this and the poet [W.H.] Auden. You know who is, right?

409
00:54:06,400 --> 00:54:11,720
Auden. He wrote a famous thing that was called "1947" [The Age of Anxiety: A Baroque Eclogue]…

410
00:54:11,720 --> 00:54:18,200
Anyway, he has a line that… And I’m not saying Auden would agree with me,

411
00:54:18,200 --> 00:54:23,540
but I’d told you chyron at the bottom of the screen saying,

412
00:54:23,540 --> 00:54:34,859
“I reserve the right to appropriate anything I’ve ever heard anyone say to promote Krishna conception.”

413
00:54:34,860 --> 00:54:44,080
The chyron at the bottom of the screen says…
So he said, “We are composed of Eros and dust.”

414
00:54:44,080 --> 00:54:50,900
And then I thought, “Yes, but it’s
not the dust… Let go of the dust part—that’s

415
00:54:50,900 --> 00:54:59,760
the part that can finish. The Eros part is
permanent. It will live on. There must be

416
00:54:59,760 --> 00:55:06,920
a domain where that aspect can be expressed—that’s
only dealt with in Krishna conception.”

417
00:55:06,920 --> 00:55:11,120
muktir hitvānyathā rūpaṁ
sva-rūpeṇa vyavasthitiḥ

418
00:55:11,120 --> 00:55:12,960
[Śrīmad Bhāgavatam 2.10.6]

419
00:55:12,960 --> 00:55:21,480
Shed… the shackle of the dust aspect. The
Eros part is permanent and has a plane of

420
00:55:21,480 --> 00:55:31,920
expression in the domain of divine love of
Krishna. So, what did I say before?

421
00:55:31,920 --> 00:55:40,619
Oh, back in the jail cell. So, then I thought… And
I had heard one devotee within the last year,

422
00:55:40,619 --> 00:55:47,880
for something that, say, in the US would have been
considered a minor infraction, was serving

423
00:55:47,880 --> 00:55:57,859
two years' internment. So I thought, “This
could be something like that. I need to take

424
00:55:57,860 --> 00:56:07,160
this very seriously and I need to prepare
myself to be confined indefinitely.

425
00:56:07,160 --> 00:56:13,580
That’s the only way I’ll be able to… If I’m
thinking this is going to end tomorrow, or

426
00:56:13,589 --> 00:56:18,770
a week from now, that won’t be good for
[me] because if not then I’m going to be

427
00:56:18,770 --> 00:56:29,910
devastated psycho-emotionally.” So I thought,
“I need to prepare myself that it could

428
00:56:29,910 --> 00:56:38,520
be indefinite confinement and when I’m okay
with that then I can proceed. It should be

429
00:56:38,520 --> 00:56:47,150
nothing less than that.” Then I thought,
“How to get to that point? Now I understand

430
00:56:47,150 --> 00:56:54,650
what I need to do. How will I get there?”
So, I chanted as much as I could and then

431
00:56:54,650 --> 00:57:05,280
I remembered, “Oh, I have my Chaitanya-charitāmṛta,”
and it turns out it was Sanātan-śikṣā,

432
00:57:05,280 --> 00:57:11,790
Mahāprabhu’s instructions to Sanātan Goswāmī,
which you may remember begins with Sanātan

433
00:57:11,790 --> 00:57:22,240
Goswāmī in jail, and while he’s in jail
he gets a letter from Rūpa Goswāmī.

434
00:57:22,240 --> 00:57:33,619
So I’m reading this with great eagerness and
anticipation. I’ve read it before but now

435
00:57:33,620 --> 00:57:41,820
it’s showing some new light to me because
of its relevance. That’s the point.

436
00:57:41,820 --> 00:57:49,260
Āchinoti yaḥ śāstrārtham [Vāyu-purāṇa].
There’s so much in the scripture what is

437
00:57:49,260 --> 00:57:56,660
relevant to us in our present situation and
circumstance—that we need to know. So, there

438
00:57:56,660 --> 00:58:08,560
is the letter of Rūpa Goswāmī to Sanātan
Goswāmī where he’s quoting a śloka and

439
00:58:08,560 --> 00:58:12,800
it says:

440
00:58:12,800 --> 00:58:25,740
yadu-pateḥ kva gatā mathurā-purī
raghu-pateḥ kva gatottara-kośalā

441
00:58:25,740 --> 00:58:34,420
iti vichintya kuruṣva manaḥ sthiraṁ
na sad idaṁ jagad ity avadhāraya

442
00:58:34,420 --> 00:58:36,040
[Śrī Chaitanya-charitāmṛta, Madhya 20.3,
Purport]

443
00:58:36,040 --> 00:58:41,740
It’s so beautiful. The only person I ever
heard quote it was Śrīla Gurudev. Once.

444
00:58:41,740 --> 00:58:47,680
At the time I had not committed it to memory.
Then I thought, “Oh, he knows that,”

445
00:58:47,680 --> 00:58:54,520
and he used it so beautifully. But what he’s
saying here and this is when the calm...—

446
00:58:54,520 --> 00:59:10,440
"manaḥ sthiraṁ" means ‘mental composure,’ more
than mental. And it’s so perfect in context

447
00:59:10,440 --> 00:59:24,340
and meaningful to devotees, aspiring devotees
as well. Yadu-pateḥ kva gatā mathurā-purī,

448
00:59:24,340 --> 00:59:30,940
saying, “Where’s the Mathurā Purī of
Yadu-pati (that means Krishna)? There was

449
00:59:30,940 --> 00:59:38,670
a time when Krishna world was here.” We
always read about Vrindāvan, and we say,

450
00:59:38,670 --> 00:59:48,720
“5000 years ago.” And he said, “Where
has it gone?” Raghu-pateḥ kva gatottara-kośalā,

451
00:59:48,720 --> 00:59:53,680
and the Raghu-vaṁśha, the dynasty of Rāmachandra and his kingdom—

452
00:59:53,680 --> 00:59:58,860
long gone to the point considered by mode of mythology.

453
00:59:58,860 --> 01:00:07,440
Vanished, withdrawn from this
plane. So he’s saying, “If the Krishna world

454
01:00:07,440 --> 01:00:15,000
withdrew from this plane, the Raghu,
Rāmachandra's, withdrew from this plane, then

455
01:00:15,000 --> 01:00:21,400
iti vichintya kuruṣva manaḥ sthiraṁ,
then make your mind steady by realizing—what?—

456
01:00:21,400 --> 01:00:33,460
Na sad idaṁ.” Na sad means ‘it’s not
real, this world—it’s not real, it’s not permanent,

457
01:00:33,460 --> 01:00:38,020
it’s temporary.’ Na sad
idaṁ jagad ity avadhāraya,

458
01:00:38,020 --> 01:00:48,780
it’s only here from some time and then it vanishes.
As that scientist says in his book.

459
01:00:48,790 --> 01:00:54,109
But don’t let the… They’ll say, “Oh,
but that’s going to happen a trillion years

460
01:00:54,109 --> 01:00:58,380
from now.” That’s what Yudhiṣṭhir
Mahārāja is telling Yamarāj saying,

461
01:00:58,380 --> 01:01:03,300
“That kind of thinking—that’s what’s astonishing,
when you know better:

462
01:01:03,300 --> 01:01:06,920
everyone before you died, everyone around us is dying,

463
01:01:06,920 --> 01:01:10,260
and now it’s been pushed in our face, and still

464
01:01:10,270 --> 01:01:16,040
we think it won’t be us.” Kim āśchāryam
ataḥ param [Mahābhārata, Vana-parva 313.116],

465
01:01:16,040 --> 01:01:18,780
what could be more astonishing than this.

466
01:01:18,780 --> 01:01:32,010
But, if we appreciate the letter of Rūpa
Goswāmī then we understand that this is

467
01:01:32,010 --> 01:01:40,980
the time when philosophy shows its value.
Deep thinking. Dive deep into Reality, beyond

468
01:01:40,980 --> 01:01:45,940
the superficial aspects of temporal existence.

469
01:01:50,260 --> 01:02:01,820
Hare Krishna. And as Guru Mahārāja says,
“Live in the world of our faith.”

470
01:02:01,820 --> 01:02:05,420
I was discussing this with
Śrīla Madhusūdan Mahārāja earlier.

471
01:02:05,420 --> 01:02:16,200
Our happiness lies in glorifying
Hari-guru and Vaiṣṇava.

472
01:02:16,200 --> 01:02:23,600
When recently was the Appearance Day of Śrīvās
Ṭhākur… And when they were in the kīrtan

473
01:02:23,610 --> 01:02:29,800
at śrīvās-aṅgaṁ—and that’s where
Mahāprabhu sang hari haraye namaḥ kṛṣṇa,

474
01:02:29,800 --> 01:02:40,360
the beginning of that—during one kīrtan
one of his sons died. He came out of the room

475
01:02:40,360 --> 01:02:46,700
saying what’s wrong. And [his] wife and
others said [that] his son died, they’re all

476
01:02:46,700 --> 01:02:51,990
crying, lamenting, and he is saying, “That
may be, but don’t disturb Mahāprabhu.

477
01:02:51,990 --> 01:03:03,020
Mahāprabhu is now in some deep ecstatic emotion.
We don’t want to disturb those divine emotions of His.”

478
01:03:03,020 --> 01:03:10,300
And you can think, “Oh, how callous is Śrīvās!”
No, he’s loving…, but this is the depth

479
01:03:10,300 --> 01:03:21,580
of his devotion that: that is real and this
is temporal. But then afterwards,

480
01:03:21,580 --> 01:03:29,300
when it comes to Mahāprabhu’s attention,
and he’s saying, “Śrīvās, why didn’t you tell me?”

481
01:03:29,300 --> 01:03:32,860
[Śrīvās] is saying, “I didn’t want to disturb You.”
And then Mahāprabhu is saying, like

482
01:03:32,860 --> 01:03:38,420
“Can I ever leave such
a devotee as this? He’s totally purchased Me

483
01:03:38,420 --> 01:03:47,360
with this type of love and affection.”
And because these are divine pastimes,

484
01:03:47,360 --> 01:03:52,320
it’s like they say at the end of the movie:
‘no animals were actually harmed in the making

485
01:03:52,330 --> 01:04:01,740
of this motion picture.’ So, no one actually
dies in these divine pastimes. No souls were

486
01:04:01,740 --> 01:04:13,080
actually extinguished. Read the Bhagavad-gītā
Chapter 2: na jāyate mriyate vā kadāchin, etc.

487
01:04:13,080 --> 01:04:24,550
But that child, who was actually, perhaps,
the child of Chitraketu in the Bhāgavatam.

488
01:04:24,550 --> 01:04:32,970
So the child is revived by Mahāprabhu, and
he starts giving a philosophical talk to everyone

489
01:04:32,970 --> 01:04:38,900
telling them that this world… This is a
child speaking now, who just died, left the world,

490
01:04:38,900 --> 01:04:42,880
then he comes back and says, “This
world is temporary. Don’t put your faith

491
01:04:42,880 --> 01:04:49,000
here and try to live permanently in this plane.
By the will of the Lord, I came here for some time

492
01:04:49,000 --> 01:04:55,860
by His will I’m leaving here now going
on to another situation. Don’t lament for me.”

493
01:04:57,140 --> 01:05:03,440
Bhakti Vichār Jājāvar Mahārāja was the
last person to take sannyās from

494
01:05:03,440 --> 01:05:16,460
Śrīla Bhakti Siddhānta Saraswatī Ṭhākur, but being a simple-hearted pure devotee

495
01:05:16,460 --> 01:05:24,680
and humble in every way. And we had the good fortune
to meet His divine grace and be bathed in

496
01:05:24,680 --> 01:05:39,069
his Vaiṣṇava vision. He thought, “What
if I can’t keep up,” when the sannyāsi

497
01:05:39,069 --> 01:05:45,609
is offered by Saraswatī Ṭhākur—“What if I can’t maintain my vows, I can’t keep the position.”

498
01:05:45,609 --> 01:05:53,560
He was fearful, afraid.

499
01:05:56,200 --> 01:05:58,940
Guru Mahārāja, when he heard…
And some devotees were saying,

500
01:05:58,940 --> 01:06:05,080
“Yes, Prabhu, what you are thinking that
is the correct thing. Tell Prabhupād you’re

501
01:06:05,100 --> 01:06:10,980
not qualified.” When Guru Mahārāja heard
this, he approached Śrīla Saraswatī Ṭhākur

502
01:06:10,980 --> 01:06:18,160
and explained the situation about the hesitation.

503
01:06:20,900 --> 01:06:28,520
I think his name was Sarvānanda—
something along those lines— Brahmachārī.

504
01:06:28,520 --> 01:06:32,700
Saraswatī Ṭhākur called him to his side, and he said,

505
01:06:32,700 --> 01:06:41,280
“When you take sannyāsi you are approaching the abhaya-pāda.” That means ‘the fearless world.’

506
01:06:41,280 --> 01:06:48,040
Like, bhajahu̐ re mana śrī-nanda-nandana /
abhaya-charaṇāravinda re.

507
01:06:48,040 --> 01:06:51,420
Kamala-dala-jala, jīvana ṭalamala—

508
01:06:51,420 --> 01:06:55,120
we see this all the time,
because we have lotus flowers here.

509
01:06:55,120 --> 01:07:01,960
When I first heard this song many years ago, I thought
it was saying, ‘water on the lotus petals.’

510
01:07:01,960 --> 01:07:07,840
That’s not what it’s saying. Because there’s
the lotus flower—that’s another story.

511
01:07:07,840 --> 01:07:12,560
So many things are said about the lotus.
This is talking about the leaf, the green leaf

512
01:07:12,569 --> 01:07:20,100
beneath the lotus flower. And you’ll see
a bead of water pooling on there. And they

513
01:07:20,109 --> 01:07:25,830
look like mirrors, actually, if you look at
them closely. But you can watch it and then

514
01:07:25,830 --> 01:07:34,840
without any indication it just suddenly rolls
off the leaf. It’s not like you go,

515
01:07:34,840 --> 01:07:41,260
“Oh, it’s gonna happen,” no, it just does it,
and that’s what he’s saying. Kamala-dala-jala,

516
01:07:41,260 --> 01:07:46,180
jīvana ṭalamala, ‘this life is like that
water on the leaf of the lotus flower—

517
01:07:46,180 --> 01:07:54,100
it can finish at any moment.’ So, Saraswatī
Ṭhākur told Jājāvar Mahārāja,

518
01:07:54,100 --> 01:08:00,560
“This is the world you should be afraid of, not
the spiritual world, going that direction—

519
01:08:00,569 --> 01:08:07,160
don’t be fearful of that.” This world, [in] which
there’s danger in every step—the ādhyātmic,

520
01:08:07,160 --> 01:08:14,140
ādhidaivic and ādhibhautic miseries, as
this present situation reminds us—

521
01:08:14,140 --> 01:08:28,520
it is inescapable. So, if anything, if this can
be used as a catalyst or, what’s the word

522
01:08:28,520 --> 01:08:36,050
for like ‘compel’ but it’s another word…
‘push’… I can’t think of… in terms

523
01:08:36,050 --> 01:08:43,020
of giving a push… Nityānanda Dās:—‘Accelerate.’
Goswāmī Mahārāja:—That’s a word.

524
01:08:43,020 --> 01:08:57,620
There is another word I’m looking for. Prachoditāḥ.
Prachodayati… Yes, all of these things.

525
01:08:57,620 --> 01:09:14,469
Can’t find a precise word but to nudge us,
to push us in the direction of internal culture.

526
01:09:14,469 --> 01:09:24,679
Self-reflection, self-analysis—it’s a
good time to reflect upon our lives—

527
01:09:24,680 --> 01:09:32,140
up to this point at present and how we shall proceed.

528
01:09:32,140 --> 01:09:35,819
But it’s what is before us right now
that is most important.

529
01:09:35,819 --> 01:09:40,250
As Guru Mahārāja liked to quote that poetry,

530
01:09:40,250 --> 01:09:45,760
Trust no Future howe’er pleasant!
Let the dead Past bury its dead!

531
01:09:45,760 --> 01:09:50,080
Act,—act, in the living Present!
Heart within, and God o’erhead!

532
01:09:50,080 --> 01:09:51,940
[The snippet from Henry Wadsworth Longfellow’s
“A Psalm of Life”

533
01:09:51,940 --> 01:09:54,000
quoted in “Loving search for
the lost servant” Śrīla Guru Mahārāja, p.3]

534
01:09:54,000 --> 01:10:05,200
Compel, compulsion to dive deep into Reality.
Hare Krishna.

